WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-US

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.418
Compositing is the act of

00:00:01.418 --> 00:00:02.085
combining two

00:00:02.085 --> 00:00:03.169
or more visual elements

00:00:03.169 --> 00:00:04.254
to create the illusion

00:00:04.254 --> 00:00:06.006
of a single, cohesive image,

00:00:06.006 --> 00:00:07.007
and is easily

00:00:07.007 --> 00:00:08.466
one of the most important aspects

00:00:08.466 --> 00:00:10.093
of any visual effects shot.

00:00:10.093 --> 00:00:11.678
This technique has existed nearly

00:00:11.678 --> 00:00:12.804
as long as film itself,

00:00:12.804 --> 00:00:14.472
with techniques like multiple exposure

00:00:14.472 --> 00:00:15.265
and traveling mattes

00:00:15.265 --> 00:00:16.683
being used very early on.

00:00:16.683 --> 00:00:18.268
Thankfully, with digital compositing

00:00:18.268 --> 00:00:19.894
and software like After Effects,

00:00:19.894 --> 00:00:21.104
achieving great visual effects

00:00:21.104 --> 00:00:22.439
is more accessible than ever.

00:00:22.439 --> 00:00:23.356
So today, we're going to be looking

00:00:23.356 --> 00:00:24.399
at five compositing

00:00:24.399 --> 00:00:24.983
tips to help

00:00:24.983 --> 00:00:27.110
you create a more convincing final image.

00:00:28.528 --> 00:00:29.237
We have an After Effects

00:00:29.237 --> 00:00:30.780
project here with a few elements

00:00:30.780 --> 00:00:31.448
to composite,

00:00:31.448 --> 00:00:32.282
and our first step

00:00:32.282 --> 00:00:32.866
is going to be

00:00:32.866 --> 00:00:34.534
to make sure our assets are properly

00:00:34.534 --> 00:00:36.036
color matched to their environment.

00:00:36.036 --> 00:00:37.287
To help this process, click

00:00:37.287 --> 00:00:38.997
this red/green/blue icon

00:00:38.997 --> 00:00:40.331
underneath your preview image.

00:00:40.331 --> 00:00:41.583
Now you can view your footage

00:00:41.583 --> 00:00:42.333
in separate red,

00:00:42.333 --> 00:00:44.169
green, and blue color channels.

00:00:44.169 --> 00:00:45.628
Now drop on a Curves effect

00:00:45.628 --> 00:00:46.588
and change the curves

00:00:46.588 --> 00:00:48.131
channel to match the color channel

00:00:48.131 --> 00:00:49.883
set on your composition window.

00:00:49.883 --> 00:00:51.468
Then tweak the respective channels

00:00:51.468 --> 00:00:52.427
to match the background

00:00:52.427 --> 00:00:53.636
as closely as possible.

00:00:53.636 --> 00:00:54.637
Once you set your channel

00:00:54.637 --> 00:00:55.889
back to RGB mode,

00:00:55.889 --> 00:00:56.514
you're going to notice

00:00:56.514 --> 00:00:57.390
how much better

00:00:57.390 --> 00:00:59.225
your assets are matching the environment.

00:00:59.225 --> 00:01:00.643
However, this only works

00:01:00.643 --> 00:01:02.062
if the lighting of your background

00:01:02.062 --> 00:01:03.521
matches the foreground element,

00:01:03.521 --> 00:01:05.190
which leads to our next tip.

00:01:06.483 --> 00:01:07.567
Matching the angle of light

00:01:07.567 --> 00:01:09.652
is crucial for any compositing shot.

00:01:09.652 --> 00:01:10.278
For example,

00:01:10.278 --> 00:01:12.113
if your background has overhead lights

00:01:12.113 --> 00:01:13.740
but your subject is lit from underneath,

00:01:13.740 --> 00:01:14.908
you're going to end up with something

00:01:14.908 --> 00:01:16.201
that feels disconnected

00:01:16.201 --> 00:01:17.243
no matter what you do.

00:01:17.243 --> 00:01:18.411
And that's why planning out

00:01:18.411 --> 00:01:19.204
your VFX shots

00:01:19.204 --> 00:01:20.413
in advance is so important.

00:01:20.413 --> 00:01:20.872
Of course,

00:01:20.872 --> 00:01:21.664
if you are building

00:01:21.664 --> 00:01:22.874
your background in 3D, 

00:01:22.874 --> 00:01:23.583
that helps a ton.

00:01:23.583 --> 00:01:24.459
But either way, 

00:01:24.459 --> 00:01:25.543
thinking about what you want

00:01:25.543 --> 00:01:26.711
your end result to be

00:01:26.711 --> 00:01:28.922
before you touch a camera is a must.

00:01:28.922 --> 00:01:30.340
So if you do know what your background

00:01:30.340 --> 00:01:31.466
is going to be before you shoot,

00:01:31.466 --> 00:01:32.842
you can have that on hand

00:01:32.842 --> 00:01:34.511
and light your subject to match.

00:01:35.720 --> 00:01:36.262
Another thing

00:01:36.262 --> 00:01:37.430
that will break your composite

00:01:37.430 --> 00:01:38.598
and sometimes can leave

00:01:38.598 --> 00:01:39.808
your composite feeling off

00:01:39.808 --> 00:01:41.184
without you fully being able

00:01:41.184 --> 00:01:42.352
to put a finger on why

00:01:42.352 --> 00:01:43.394
is your black levels.

00:01:43.394 --> 00:01:44.437
Like the angle of light,

00:01:44.437 --> 00:01:45.647
this will be a dead giveaway

00:01:45.647 --> 00:01:46.439
that your assets

00:01:46.439 --> 00:01:47.732
live in different worlds.

00:01:47.732 --> 00:01:48.525
And like I said,

00:01:48.525 --> 00:01:50.193
it can be hard to diagnose

00:01:50.193 --> 00:01:52.195
sometimes if the issue is subtle enough.

00:01:52.195 --> 00:01:53.113
So to correct this,

00:01:53.113 --> 00:01:54.155
we'll go to Window &gt;

00:01:54.155 --> 00:01:55.156
Lumetri Scopes,

00:01:55.156 --> 00:01:56.616
and now you'll have a better view

00:01:56.616 --> 00:01:57.534
of your black levels.

00:01:57.534 --> 00:01:59.369
So now using this as our guide,

00:01:59.369 --> 00:02:00.954
we'll use our curves to adjust

00:02:00.954 --> 00:02:02.163
and get one step closer

00:02:02.163 --> 00:02:03.706
to that convincing shot.

00:02:04.958 --> 00:02:05.792
This next one doesn't

00:02:05.792 --> 00:02:06.835
apply to all projects,

00:02:06.835 --> 00:02:08.336
but if you are masking an element

00:02:08.336 --> 00:02:10.046
with hard and soft edges,

00:02:10.046 --> 00:02:11.381
using the regular pen tool

00:02:11.381 --> 00:02:13.216
can lead to inconsistent feathering.

00:02:13.216 --> 00:02:14.175
The fix this, once you

00:02:14.175 --> 00:02:15.426
have your asset masked out,

00:02:15.426 --> 00:02:16.761
you can hold down the Pen Tool

00:02:16.761 --> 00:02:18.555
and select the Mask Feather Tool.

00:02:18.555 --> 00:02:20.181
Now you can add feather gradients

00:02:20.181 --> 00:02:22.100
to different areas of the mask to help

00:02:22.100 --> 00:02:23.560
match the varied edges,

00:02:23.560 --> 00:02:25.687
leading to a more natural effect.

00:02:26.980 --> 00:02:28.690
Our last tip is using a spill suppressor

00:02:28.690 --> 00:02:29.274
to remove

00:02:29.274 --> 00:02:31.151
any of your original background color

00:02:31.151 --> 00:02:32.527
that leaked into the foreground.

00:02:32.527 --> 00:02:33.194
You can add this

00:02:33.194 --> 00:02:34.445
by going up to Effects &gt;

00:02:34.445 --> 00:02:35.613
Keying, and clicking

00:02:35.613 --> 00:02:37.157
Advanced Spill Suppressor.

00:02:37.157 --> 00:02:39.117
You can keep your method at Standard

00:02:39.117 --> 00:02:40.160
if that works for you,

00:02:40.160 --> 00:02:41.786
or you can change it to Ultra.

00:02:41.786 --> 00:02:43.329
Then select your key color.

00:02:43.329 --> 00:02:44.205
to finish it all off.

00:02:44.205 --> 00:02:45.123
You can add some grain

00:02:45.123 --> 00:02:46.499
to glue everything together

00:02:46.499 --> 00:02:48.459
and you will have your composited shot.

00:02:48.459 --> 00:02:48.960
But there you have it.

00:02:48.960 --> 00:02:49.586
A few tips

00:02:49.586 --> 00:02:51.171
to sell your compositing effects.

00:02:51.171 --> 00:02:52.005
And if you have something

00:02:52.005 --> 00:02:53.423
you'd like to see us cover in the future,

00:02:53.423 --> 00:02:55.175
feel free to drop a comment below.

00:02:55.300 --> 00:02:56.718
And don't forget to like and subscribe,

00:02:56.718 --> 00:02:58.261
because honey never spoils.

00:02:58.261 --> 00:03:00.180
Even after thousands of years.

00:03:00.180 --> 00:03:01.306
And you're my honey.

